Title: Come out 2 Nite
Comment:
To be honest, Kenickie made me feel old as shit even when I was a teenager, as they were clearly having way more fun than me (I was more likely to "Stay in 2 Nite").

But many years later that feeling has been intensified, partly just by the nostalgia, but also by the cognitive dissonance of singer Lauren Laverne now being a respectable mainstream broadcaster for the BBC.

Comment: This song is now 20+ years old, and not only does it make me think of Scrubs (which has been off the air for over a decade), it also makes me tear up like a big baby whenever I listen to it.

Title: Pass The Dutchie
Comment: This is my submission! This damn song came out the year I was born (1983), which makes me feel old AS FUCK. But this tune, as old as it may be, still makes me feel young and fresh. Whenever I‚Äôm feeling like a sad old sack of shit I can always pass the dutchie ‚Äòpon the left hand side

Title: The Moon Is Down
Comment: Realizing that "new" albums are now decades old really hits hard. I remember listening to this song/album in middle school and loving it. Then Carrabba left, and I didn't care for the new guy on "How to Start a Fire." Of course, there were some great albums from Dashboard before their "new stuff," which I also didn't care for. Now all that "new stuff" is roughly 20 years old, and there are so many upsetting milestones that highlight this. This all is second only to watching a child or pet age.

Title: Visiting Hours
Comment: I found this band in high school when I got algorithmed or something I think(I found them like 9 years after this song came out). There's some nostalgic aging, but honestly I feel old in a much more endogenous way most of the time. What really makes me feel old about this is realizing that the LDR that changed how I experienced it ended 5 years ago and now I'm 24 and lonely and still kinda busted up for a bunch of reasons. I was bad at the mind mindgames round so I'm doing it now. Pity vote?

Title: Siva - Remastered 2011
Comment: I had a best friend in my teens and 20s who was a drummer and used to love pointing out great drumming in songs. Loved Jimmy Chamberlain from Smashing Pumpkins and we used to hammer the "best of" album. And then I left our hometown and we drifted apart and I've not really had a friend as close since and I miss that. But this song reminds me of being young and buying CDs and listening to them in my kitchen with my friends.

Title: Skylines and Turnstiles
Album: I Brought You My Bullets, You Brought Me Your Love
Comment: Makes me feel old for so many reasons (disclaimer: I am 25). Skylines and Turnstiles was the first song Gerard Way (My Chemical Romance, Umbrella Academy, Doom Patrol) wrote after witnessing the towers fall on 9/11. It moved him to write this song about the grief and confusion he and the rest of the American public felt about the tragedy. It's one of the only songs about the event I can stand listening to bc of how sincere it is. This song came out in 2002 and helped kick off MCR's legacy.

Title: Seventeener (17th and 37th)
Comment: Hear me out - I'm 22, there's not a lot that really makes me feel old. BUT, this song has gotten the closest to helping me visualize what I'd imagine getting old is like, so it's the closest I can submit to the prompt, and I hope you will consider that when voting.

Title: Our Town
Comment:
This is one of my all-time favorite songs. Just so, so beautiful and bittersweet. It goes over many facets and milestones of life.

Title: Time to Pretend
Comment: Under the bouncy beat and flippant tone, it‚Äôs actually a pretty depressing song about adulthood just on its own. But it will also always vividly capture a specific era: Tumblr, American Apparel skater dresses and leggings, first iPhones, actual Brooklyn hipsters, rise of Obama, etc. and every time I listen to this song and get transported back and then think about how long ago that all was now, I need to go lie down

Title: Castle Door
Comment:
"You awaken in a cold, dimly lit cell. The air is damp and heavy. The only door, made of heavy iron, is locked tight. Panic sets in. What do you do?"

1. Search the Cell (4 votes): Carefully search for hidden objects or clues.

2. Call for Help (6 votes): Shout or make noise to attract attention.

3. Examine the Door (8 votes): Inspect the door for weaknesses or unlocking methods.

Choose wisely! Your decision shapes your fate. Comment with your vote!

Title: Agnes - Radio Edit
Comment:
Love this video. Filmed in a human centrifuge, it's supposed to replicate the immense pressure the character 'Agnes' was under. You can literally see the singer struggling to complete it, approaching the brink of unconsciousness as the video goes on (he passed out in one take), and they ran through the song and the centrifuge 18 times until they got it right.

Chose the radio edit because it more closely matches the video
